        <div class="pt-5">
            <div class="heading col-8"><span class="headingid"> 2. </span>THE FIRST HUNDRED YEARS</div>
            <div class="subheading container"><span class="subheadingid"> 2.1. </span>MISSIONARIES AND THE COLONIAL ERA </div>
            
            <div class="contant container">
                <p><b>A School that Reflects Kandy's Unique Culture is Born</b></p>
                <p>Trinity College is firmly rooted in the pluralistic culture and atmosphere that is Kandy, the last holdout of the country's ancient kingdoms. And it is this uniqueness that sets the College apart from the many other Private Schools founded by Christian Missionaries in the late 19th century.</p>
                <p>As Prof Gananath Obesekere, the renowned academic notes in his book " The Doomed King, " though the mountain kingdom may have been a citadel for the Sinhala monarchs it boasted a great cosmopolitan culture. </p>
                <p>Fr. Joseph Vaas, the first saint of the Catholic Church in Sri Lanka was one of many who found refuge in Kandy. Then, there were the Arab traders who made this Kingdom their home, to conduct their business with the people of Kandy. as did the many European and East Asian soldiers who, as Robert Knox notes, spent their captivity, living amongst the Kandyans.</p>
                <p>The goal for the Anglican Missionaries who created and helmed Trinity for the first fifty or so years was to train Ceylonese youth to become Colonial Administrators. With that purpose in mind, they brought to the school the best of the English Public - School traditions.</p>
                <p>Through careful observations of the lives and history of the people of Kandy, the first missionaries realised that these were a people that firmly clung to their cultural identity.</p>
                <p>The missionaries " recognised the need to respect the world the school was part of, and despite their zealous faith, were compelled to offer the education that the people of the Central Highlands wanted. This gave Trinity a particular ' tone and ' shade ' that no other missionary school in Ceylon could claim. It is marked by a sensitivity to the vernacular. An ability to juggle social hierarchies and an unexpected tolerance of religious and ethnic differences are its hallmarks " wrote Ramya Chamila Jayasinghe in " Trinity " the book that marked the Centenary of the Colombo Old Boys Association.</p>
                <p>In essence, Kandy created Trinity in its own form. The " Colonial Project ", for some an offensive phrase, was to educate and train the sons of the local " Chieftains and to use a common Hindi phrase, make them " Pukka Sahibs " or gentlemen in the British mould. But the strong cultural strength of the capital of the Kandyan kingdom asserted itself.</p>
                <p>We track the age of Trinity College from January 17 , 1872 although the original school known as the Kandy Collegiate School, was started in 1857 by Rev. 1 Ireland Jones. On his departure, the school was closed in 1863. It was reopened in 1876 and renamed Trinity College Kandy. The author of the History of Trinity, Valesca Reiman quotes an annual report of the Christian Missionary Society to say that the school derives its name from the Trinity Church which was in the vicinity of the school.</p>
                <p>The founder Principal of Trinity College Kandy was Rev. Richard Collins. Some historians claim that the school got its name as Rev. Collins was an alumnus of Trinity College, Dublin.</p>
                <p>Following a six - year stint by Rev. Collins , the school faced some tumakyous years going through several Principals, who served relatively short terms.</p>
                <p>First, there was Rev. J G Garrett who led the school for five years. When he left due to ill - health , Rev. EN Hodges took over but was transferred by the Church after three short years . The Rev. EJ Perry who followed him was an experienced school administrator and brilliant scholar. However, rather unfortunately he died when he was accidentally shot by a student while on a trip to Bintenne . during the Easter Holiday. He served for just a year.</p>
                <p>In the next ten years, Trinity went through a transformation under Principal. Rev H.P.Napier - Clavering , M.A.of Trinity College , Cambridge , and a Master at Monkton Coombe School. He took over the school in 1890. The Centenary Number notes, " the great spirit of enthusiasm that had been stirred up by Mr. Perry and on this, he built a school the near equal of any in Ceylon. He first put it on a sound financial footing, added to the available accommodation, and constructed new classrooms. The school magazine came out , a Cricket Club was flourishing, the Cadet Corps was getting into its stride, and he helped form an Old Boys ' Association. This was the time when TCK got a sound foundation and strived to produce " all - rounders ", boys who were multi - dimensional and multi - skilled.</p>
                <p>" Mr. Napier - Clavering's successor was Rev. R W Ryde who was with Trinity for just two years. Thereafter, a succession of Principals helmed Trinity, with Mr. Napier - Clavering returning three times in an acting capacity.</p>
                <p><b>A.G. Fraser</b></p>
                <p>Then came the man, who was to be the biggest influencer in the history of the school, the Rev. A G. Fraser , who took over the Principalship in 1904 and held the post for 20 years , even though he was away for long periods.</p>
                <br>
                <div class="subcontant container">
                    <p>
                        <figure class="figureChap2">
                            <img src="assets/images/chap1img1.png" alt="image" class="">
