                    </p>
                    <p><b>Fraser Legacy</b></p>
                    <p>In 1910, six years after taking over as Principal, Alek Fraser was contemplating leaving Trinity to take up a post in the International Missionary Conference. In rejecting the move, the secretary of the CMS wrote to Fraser stating " We all agree that the position of Trinity College, Kandy, is tied up for the present in your I personality. The first three decades of TCK were marked by the faltering struggles of her founding Principals - many brilliant scholars among them to build an educational institution of national repute. If it took Fraser six years to turn things around by his sheer force of personality, in the course of twenty years, he would build an institutional legacy that would last a century.</p>
                    <p>He appreciated the transformative power of education on individuals and its foundational importance at societal scale. Perhaps more critically, he had a worldview that was nimble and sophisticated enough to understand that the elements of a sound education needed to be rooted in the student's cultural and historical context for them to be attu ed to the world around them, and well equipped to heed their calling as citizens. As a contemporary and admirer of Cecil Earle Tyndale - Biscoe, Fraser believed that schools had an active role to play in their community. Fraser was born two decades after the publication of Darwin's " The Origin of Species " and the subsequent split between Christian theology and science. Yet as a missionary educator, he crafted Trinity as a bastion of liberal values : free inquiry, scientific exploration, plurality of faith and inclusivity.</p>
                    <p>Alek Garden Fraser did have his failings too. He is often described as tough minded and uncompromising, and at times fiery. He is said to have been too quick to judge and draw false conclusions, and yet with enough humility to apologise to anyone he may have treated unfairly. And yet he had the good judgement and enough broadmindedness to recruit to his staff, teachers who would leave equally profound and long - lasting imprints on the character and traditions of the school. Whether it is the poetry of Senior that we admire or studies in I comparative religion that men like Saunders pioneered at school level. or the great traditions of social service that defined the Trinity identity and ethos which Norman Campbell instituted, it is worth remembering that these were all men that Fraser had hand - picked to join his staff. Rev. Gaster, to whose vision and legacy the college chapel bears witness, was not hand - pick by Fraser himself, but his path to Trinity would have been impossible, if not for Fraser's determination and fight.</p>
                    <p>As an administrator, Fraser had a clear vision which he often had to fight to realise. However, the long tenure that made possible his many great achievements, and ultimately his lasting legacy, owes as much to the trust he was able to establish even with those whom he fiercely disagreed , as much as to the force of his personality. Even though 1 many disagreed with him and some fell out ( and some even found him difficult to work with ) very few doubted his integrity or the fact that his fight was not personal but on matters of policy. In fact, he maintained great personal relations even with those whom he fiercely disagreed with.</p>
                    <p>1 There is no doubt however, that much of Trinity and the country has transformed beyond recognition in the century that separates the tenure of Alek Garden Fraser from the present. His legacy continues to inspire Trinitians, but not because we are able to recount what he did. nor even for knowing who he was, but for what he built. Even though the Chapel was constructed by his successors, its design and foundation were laid in his time and its form and architectural vision bear the imprint of Fraser's values and vision. It stands unambiguously as a place of Christian worship, both confident and authentic in the expression of its identity, like the school Fraser intended to build. And so, with Asgiriya - perhaps Trinity's greatest monument - Fraser has left encoded lessons that Trinitians will decipher and learn to apply in their time and place, for generations to come.</p>
                </div><br>
                <p>He had a powerful personality and inspired people he encountered to be loyal, and to be of service. Mr. Fraser was also good at choosing the right man for the right job. A great organiser, his powerful influence stayed with the College and for many, Trinity's name is synonymous with that of Fraser.</p>
                <p>He transformed the education system of the school.</p>
                <p>Trinity was designed to produce a complete individual, and Mr. Fraser sought to achieve that goal through many methods . The boys were taught to be alert in mind and body. He ensured they were well disciplined and conscious of their obligation to the society around them . The Social Service Union he started saw its members, the sons of the Kandyan elite visiting underserved communities around Mahaiyawa and cleaning and dressing the wounds of Sanitation workers.</p>
                <p>Students were encouraged to be selfless in their service, or in the least to do honest job in any profession they pursued.</p>
                <p>Indeed, it is this " Trinity Spirit ", instilled in students and staff all those long years ago that endures even today.</p>
                <p>As the former Vice Principal Hilary Abeyaratne, the author of the Centenary Number wrote " Above all, however, Mr.Fraser gave to Trinity a tone, an atmosphere, that is peculiarly its own . It was he who stressed and emphasized the need for a religious background to education ; it was he who realised , more than most contemporaries did , the need to synthesize the heritage of the East with what was best in the West."</p>
